3. Anchor gets formal distinction from Lock
This was an important correction.
	•	Lock / Invariant = what is discovered to remain stable
	•	Anchor = what is deliberately fixed to stabilize reasoning or execution

So:
	•	Lock is found
	•	Anchor is placed

This matters across many Pantheon systems.

Mirror and Checksum care about discovered invariants.
Mother Duck, Goblin, and implementation layers often require deliberate anchors.

This distinction should be made explicit in doctrine.

⸻

4. Structural vs ethical invariants
Another strong Claude refinement.

Not all invariants are the same.
	•	Structural invariants are discovered properties that survive transforms
	•	Ethical invariants are constraints that must remain preserved whether or not the system naturally wants to preserve them

This is a major governance improvement.

It aligns perfectly with existing Pantheon ethics ≥ 0.7 framing.

